vectorData.altText: Identify the cells of the posterior pituitary, B.

That's right! The nuclei present in the posterior pituitary belong to glial cells called pituicytes. The nuclei of the neurosecretory cells are in the paraventricular and supraoptic nuclei of the hypothalamus. Only the axon terminals of the neurosecretory cells are present in the posterior pituitary.

H10   Histology of the Posterior Pituitary

The posterior pituitary contains unmyelinated axons and their terminals, their cell bodies of origin being in the supraoptic and paraventricular nuclei of the hypothalamus. The glial cells that surround these nerve processes are called pituicytes (P).  
Swellings in the nerve terminals called neurosecretory (Herring) bodies (NB) release either oxytocin or antidiuretic hormone into the surrounding interstitial fluid.
These hormones diffuse into the fenestrated capillaries (C) of the posterior pituitary for transport.
